What is XPath?

XPath (XML Path Language) is a syntax used to locate elements on a web page using XML path expressions.
It allows us to find elements based on their HTML DOM structure and navigate through nodes, elements,
and attributes within the Document Object Model (DOM).

Types of XPath
1. Absolute XPath / Full XPath
    Starts from the root node of the HTML document.
    Example:  /html/body/div[6]/div[1]/div[2]/div[2]/form/input

2. Relative XPath / Partial XPath
    Directly targets the element without starting from the root.
    Example: //input[@id='small-searchterms']

General XPath Syntax
 //tagName[@attribute='value']

Difference Between Absolute XPath & Relative XPath
Absolute XPath	                                 Relative XPath
Starts from the root node	                     Does not start from the root; jumps directly to the element
Begins with / (single slash)	                 Begins with // (double slash)
Uses only tags/nodes	                         Uses attributes, functions, and conditions

XPath Options / Functions
or               //tagName[@attribute='value' or @attribute = 'value']
and              //tagName[@attribute='value' and @attribute = 'value']
contains()       //tagName[contains(@attribute, 'value')]
starts-with()    //tagName[starts-with(@attribute, 'value')]
text()           //tagName[text() = 'value']
Chained XPath    //tagName[@attribute = 'value']//tagName[@attribute = 'value']


XPath Axes
self                //tag[@attr='value']/self::tag
parent              //tag[@attr='value']/parent::parentTag
child               //tag[@attr='value']/child::childTag
ancestor            //tag[@attr='value']/ancestor::ancestorTag
descendant          //tag[@attr='value']/descendant::descendantTag
following           //tag[@attr='value']/following::tag
following-sibling   //tag[@attr='value']/following-sibling::tag
preceding           //tag[@attr='value']/preceding::tag
preceding-sibling   //tag[@attr='value']/preceding-sibling::tag
